Running this with deno run and opening the web page shows the graph directly (after having some data-points ofc)
Running this with deno desktop the graph is not show until i manually reload the page

Cause: i didn't debug this , but my guess js is being lazy loaded or something 

main.ts

```ts
#!/usr/bin/env -S deno run --allow-net --allow-run --allow-env --unstable-kv
/**
 * Speedtest monitor: runs `speedtest` (Ookla CLI) on an interval, stores
 * results in Deno KV, and serves a chart over HTTP.
 *
 * Requires the python `speedtest-cli` (sivel/speedtest-cli) on PATH:
 *   https://github.com/sivel/speedtest-cli
 *   (Fedora: `sudo dnf install speedtest-cli`)
 *
 * Config (env vars):
 *   PORT                     default 8787
 *   SPEEDTEST_INTERVAL_HOURS default 1 (accepts decimals, e.g. 0.5)
 *   RUN_ON_START             default true
 *   HISTORY_LIMIT            default 500 (points kept in the chart response)
 *
 * Run:
 *   deno run --allow-net --allow-run --allow-env --unstable-kv main.ts
 */

interface SpeedtestResult {
  timestamp: string; // ISO
  downloadMbps: number;
  uploadMbps: number;
  pingMs: number;
  server: string;
  isp: string;
  resultUrl: string | null;
}

const PORT = Number(Deno.env.get("PORT") ?? 8787);
const INTERVAL_HOURS = Number(Deno.env.get("SPEEDTEST_INTERVAL_HOURS") ?? 1);
const RUN_ON_START = (Deno.env.get("RUN_ON_START") ?? "true") !== "false";
const HISTORY_LIMIT = Number(Deno.env.get("HISTORY_LIMIT") ?? 500);

const kv = await Deno.openKv();

let running = false;

async function runSpeedtest(): Promise<SpeedtestResult | null> {
  if (running) {
    console.log("speedtest already in progress, skipping");
    return null;
  }
  running = true;
  const startedAt = new Date().toISOString();
  console.log(`[${startedAt}] running speedtest...`);
  try {
    const cmd = new Deno.Command("speedtest-cli", {
      args: ["--json", "--secure"],
      stdout: "piped",
      stderr: "piped",
    });
    const { code, stdout, stderr } = await cmd.output();
    if (code !== 0) {
      console.error(
        "speedtest-cli exited non-zero:",
        new TextDecoder().decode(stderr),
      );
      return null;
    }
    const raw = JSON.parse(new TextDecoder().decode(stdout));
    // speedtest-cli --json: download/upload are bit/s already, ping is ms.
    const result: SpeedtestResult = {
      timestamp: startedAt,
      downloadMbps: +(raw.download / 1_000_000).toFixed(2),
      uploadMbps: +(raw.upload / 1_000_000).toFixed(2),
      pingMs: +Number(raw.ping).toFixed(2),
      server: `${raw.server?.sponsor ?? "?"} (${raw.server?.name ?? "?"})`,
      isp: raw.client?.isp ?? "?",
      resultUrl: raw.share ?? null,
    };
    await kv.set(["speedtest", result.timestamp], result);
    console.log(
      `  -> down ${result.downloadMbps} Mbps / up ${result.uploadMbps} Mbps / ping ${result.pingMs} ms`,
    );
    return result;
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("speedtest run failed:", err);
    return null;
  } finally {
    running = false;
  }
}

async function getResults(limit = HISTORY_LIMIT): Promise<SpeedtestResult[]> {
  const results: SpeedtestResult[] = [];
  for await (
    const entry of kv.list<SpeedtestResult>({ prefix: ["speedtest"] })
  ) {
    results.push(entry.value);
  }
  results.sort((a, b) => a.timestamp.localeCompare(b.timestamp));
  return results.slice(-limit);
}

function scheduleLoop() {
  const ms = INTERVAL_HOURS * 60 * 60 * 1000;
  console.log(`scheduling speedtest every ${INTERVAL_HOURS}h (${ms}ms)`);
  setInterval(runSpeedtest, ms);
  if (RUN_ON_START) runSpeedtest();
}

const HTML = `<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">
<title>Speedtest monitor</title>
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js@4.5.1/dist/chart.umd.min.js"></script>
<style>
  :root { color-scheme: dark; }
  body { font-family: system-ui, sans-serif; background: #0f1115; color: #e6e6e6; margin: 0; padding: 24px; }
  h1 { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 600; margin: 0 0 4px; }
  #meta { color: #9aa0a6; font-size: 13px; margin-bottom: 20px; }
  .card { background: #1a1d24; border-radius: 10px; padding: 16px; margin-bottom: 20px; }
  table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 13px; }
  th, td { text-align: left; padding: 6px 10px; border-bottom: 1px solid #2a2e37; }
  th { color: #9aa0a6; font-weight: 500; }
  button { background: #2a2e37; color: #e6e6e6; border: none; padding: 8px 14px; border-radius: 6px; cursor: pointer; }
  button:hover { background: #383e4a; }
  button:disabled { opacity: 0.5; cursor: default; }
</style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Speedtest monitor</h1>
  <div id="meta">loading...</div>
  <div class="card"><canvas id="chart" height="90"></canvas></div>
  <div class="card">
    <button id="run">Run now</button>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <table id="tbl">
      <thead><tr><th>Time</th><th>Down (Mbps)</th><th>Up (Mbps)</th><th>Ping (ms)</th><th>Server</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody></tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
<script>
let chart;

function fmt(ts) {
  return new Date(ts).toLocaleString();
}

async function load() {
  const res = await fetch('/api/results');
  const data = await res.json();
  const meta = document.getElementById('meta');
  meta.textContent = data.length
    ? \`\${data.length} results, latest \${fmt(data[data.length - 1].timestamp)}\`
    : 'no results yet';

  const labels = data.map(d => fmt(d.timestamp));
  const download = data.map(d => d.downloadMbps);
  const upload = data.map(d => d.uploadMbps);
  const ping = data.map(d => d.pingMs);

  if (!chart) {
    chart = new Chart(document.getElementById('chart'), {
      type: 'line',
      data: {
        labels,
        datasets: [
          { label: 'Download (Mbps)', data: download, borderColor: '#4ade80', tension: 0.25, yAxisID: 'y' },
          { label: 'Upload (Mbps)', data: upload, borderColor: '#60a5fa', tension: 0.25, yAxisID: 'y' },
          { label: 'Ping (ms)', data: ping, borderColor: '#f472b6', tension: 0.25, yAxisID: 'y1' },
        ],
      },
      options: {
        responsive: true,
        interaction: { mode: 'index', intersect: false },
        scales: {
          y: { position: 'left', title: { display: true, text: 'Mbps' } },
          y1: { position: 'right', title: { display: true, text: 'ms' }, grid: { drawOnChartArea: false } },
        },
      },
    });
  } else {
    chart.data.labels = labels;
    chart.data.datasets[0].data = download;
    chart.data.datasets[1].data = upload;
    chart.data.datasets[2].data = ping;
    chart.update();
  }

  const tbody = document.querySelector('#tbl tbody');
  tbody.innerHTML = data.slice().reverse().slice(0, 30).map(d => \`
    <tr>
      <td>\${fmt(d.timestamp)}</td>
      <td>\${d.downloadMbps}</td>
      <td>\${d.uploadMbps}</td>
      <td>\${d.pingMs}</td>
      <td>\${d.server}</td>
    </tr>\`).join('');
}

document.getElementById('run').addEventListener('click', async (e) => {
  e.target.disabled = true;
  e.target.textContent = 'running...';
  try {
    await fetch('/api/run', { method: 'POST' });
  } finally {
    e.target.disabled = false;
    e.target.textContent = 'Run now';
    load();
  }
});

load();
setInterval(load, 30_000);
</script>
</body>
</html>`;

Deno.serve({ port: PORT }, async (req) => {
  const url = new URL(req.url);

  if (url.pathname === "/api/results") {
    return Response.json(await getResults());
  }

  if (url.pathname === "/api/run" && req.method === "POST") {
    const result = await runSpeedtest();
    return Response.json(
      result ?? { error: "speedtest failed, check server logs" },
      {
        status: result ? 200 : 500,
      },
    );
  }

  if (url.pathname === "/") {
    return new Response(HTML, {
      headers: { "content-type": "text/html; charset=utf-8" },
    });
  }

  return new Response("not found", { status: 404 });
});

scheduleLoop();
console.log(`serving on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
```

Version: Deno 2.9.2

Given the following files:

`deno.json`
```json
{
  "name": "@my-company/my-package",
  "version": "0.1.0",
  "exports": "./mod.ts",
  "license": "MIT",
  "imports": {
    "@std/assert": "jsr:@std/assert@1"
  }
}
```

`mod.ts`
```typescript
import { assertEquals } from "@std/assert";
import { assertAlmostEquals } from "jsr:@std/assert@1";

export function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  assertEquals(a, b);
  assertAlmostEquals(b, 4);
  return a + b;
}
```

`deno pack` produces the following `mod.js` (with source map elided):
```javascript
import { assertEquals } from "@std/assert";
import { assertAlmostEquals } from "@jsr/std__assert";
export function add(a, b) {
  assertEquals(a, b);
  assertAlmostEquals(b, 4);
  return a + b;
}
```

In this case, when a JSR dependency is written inline it is converted to the `@jsr/scope__package` format as suggested by the docs (https://docs.deno.com/runtime/reference/cli/pack/#specifier-rewriting), but when it is included in the `"imports"` field of `deno.json` it is not rewritten.

Is this the intended behaviour? I had interpreted the docs to suggest that both would be rewritten.

## Summary

If a `ReadableStream` is transferred to a `Worker` and then **cancelled while it is still open** (its
source has not reached the end), the transfer's internal `MessagePort` is never closed, and
`Deno.test`'s resource sanitizer reports:

```
Leaks detected:
  - A message port was created during the test, but not closed during the test.
    Close the message port by calling `messagePort.close()`.
```

The leak is specific and reproducible:

- **Draining** the transferred stream to completion does **not** leak (the port closes on end-of-stream).
- **Cancelling** a transferred stream that has **already reached its end** does **not** leak (no-op).
- **Cancelling while still open** (unread data pending) **does** leak.
- Only the **readable** side is affected — aborting a transferred `WritableStream` does not leak.
- It is a **permanent** leak, not a sanitizer race: adding a delay before the test ends (with or
  without `worker.terminate()`) does not clear it, and there is no JS-visible `MessagePort` to
  `close()` — the port is internal to the stream-transfer machinery.

## Version

```
deno 2.9.2 (stable, release, aarch64-apple-darwin)
v8 14.9.207.2-rusty
typescript 6.0.3
```

## Reproduction

`repro_test.js` (single file, no dependencies):

```js
const workerCode = `
self.onmessage = async (e) => {
	const { readable, action, reads } = e.data;
	const reader = readable.getReader();
	if (action === "drain") {
		for (; ;) { const { done } = await reader.read(); if (done) break; }
	} else { // "cancel"
		for (let i = 0; i < reads; i++) { const { done } = await reader.read(); if (done) break; }
		await reader.cancel("stop");
	}
	self.postMessage("done");
};
`;
const WORKER_URL = "data:text/javascript," + encodeURIComponent(workerCode);

function makeReadable({ infinite = false, count = 4 } = {}) {
	let pulls = 0;
	return new ReadableStream({
		pull(controller) {
			controller.enqueue(new Uint8Array(16));
			if (!infinite && ++pulls >= count) { controller.close(); }
		}
	});
}

async function run({ action, infinite, count, reads }) {
	const worker = new Worker(WORKER_URL, { type: "module" });
	const readable = makeReadable({ infinite, count });
	const done = new Promise(resolve => { worker.onmessage = resolve; });
	worker.postMessage({ readable, action, reads }, [readable]);
	await done;
	worker.terminate();
}

Deno.test("drain a transferred ReadableStream to completion (no leak)", () => run({ action: "drain", count: 4 }));
Deno.test("cancel a still-open transferred ReadableStream (leaks a MessagePort)", () => run({ action: "cancel", infinite: true, reads: 1 }));
Deno.test("cancel a fully-read transferred ReadableStream (no leak)", () => run({ action: "cancel", count: 4, reads: 5 }));
```

Run:

```
deno test --allow-read repro_test.js
```

## Actual

```
drain a transferred ReadableStream to completion (no leak) ... ok
cancel a still-open transferred ReadableStream (leaks a MessagePort) ... FAILED
    -> Leaks detected: A message port was created ... but not closed
cancel a fully-read transferred ReadableStream (no leak) ... ok
```

## Expected

All three pass. Cancelling a transferred (still-open) `ReadableStream` should close the transfer's
`MessagePort`, the same way draining it to completion does.

## Notes

- Found in [zip.js](https://github.com/gildas-lormeau/zip.js), which transfers a codec's input stream
  to a web worker. Any operation that ends early (wrong password, truncated/invalid data, an explicit
  early abort such as "check password only") cancels the still-open transferred input and trips this.
  Draining the entire input on error just to avoid the leak would defeat early-abort, so there is no
  reasonable userland workaround other than disabling stream transfer or opting the affected tests out
  of the resource sanitizer.

