pnpm 11.1 [added](https://github.com/pnpm/pnpm/pull/11324) [`namedRegistries`](https://pnpm.io/settings#namedregistries) after enabling support for [`jsr:`](https://github.com/pnpm/pnpm/pull/9358), which lets you define registry aliases and use them as a protocol prefix in dependency specifiers, same idea as [vlt's registry aliases](https://docs.vlt.sh/cli/registries):

```yaml
namedRegistries:
  work: https://npm.example.com/
```

```json
{
  "dependencies": {
    "@work/constants": "work:1.x.x"
  }
}
```

Unlike `.npmrc` scope mappings this is per-specifier, not per-scope, so the same scope can be served from different registries depending on the package. There's no way to express that with the existing config.

Deno can't resolve these specifiers and has nowhere to define the aliases. The part where it hit me is that this isn't limited to `deno add work:pkg` - the moment any transitive dependency in the npm graph uses a named-registry specifier, resolution of the whole graph fails, even when the top-level install was a plain `npm:` specifier.

I filed the same request against nub ([nubjs/nub#440](https://github.com/nubjs/nub/issues/440), implemented in [nubjs/nub#444](https://github.com/nubjs/nub/pull/444)).

I assume Deno reading pnpm config (local or global) is a non-starter, so the aliases would need a home in `deno.json`, something like:

```jsonc
{
  "npmNamedRegistries": {
    "work": "https://npm.work.example.com/",
    "gh": "https://npm.pkg.github.example.com/"
  }
}
```

With that in place, `npm:work:@corp/lib@^2.0.0` (and `deno add work:@corp/lib`) would resolve against the aliased registry, and named-registry specifiers found in dependency manifests would resolve the same way. For reference, pnpm accepts `<alias>:<range>`, `<alias>:<name>@<range>`, `<alias>:@owner/name@<range>` and `<alias>:<tag>`.

Auth shouldn't need anything new: the per-URL `.npmrc` entries Deno already reads (`//npm.work.example.com/:_authToken=...`) cover it.

